rwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland","Northallerton, Yorkshire, England":"Northallerton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Gordon Berwickshire, Scotland":"Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom"," Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gordon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Gordon in Berwickshire, named with Welsh <i>gor</i> ‘spacious’ + <i>din</i> ‘fort’.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Gourdon in Saône-et-Loire, so called from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Gordus</i> + the locative suffix <i>-o</i>, <i>-ōnis</i>.","English (of Norman origin): alternatively, said to be a nickname from a diminutive of Old French <i>gourd</i> ‘heavy, dull, sluggish’ (compare 8 below)."],"variants":[{"name":"Gordin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Eyal, Moisey, Yakov, Zalman, Erez, Faina, Haya, Mendel.  Russian Leonid, Aleksandr, Boris, Feiga, Genady.","Jewish (from Russia): variant of   Gordon   5.","French: variant of   Gourdin  . This surname is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Gordan","meanings":["German: variant of   Jordan  . The surname <i>Gordan</i> is very rare in Germany.","Irish (Wexford and Sligo): adopted as an Anglicized form of <b>Mag Mhuirneacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Muirneachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>muirneach</i> ‘lovable’."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Adam de Gordon 1st Laird Of Gordon was born about 1080, in Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Adam de Gordon, was 37 and his mother, Mrs Adam De Gordon, was 34. He married Lady Alicia De Gordon about 1125, in Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 22 August 1138, in Northallerton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"Abt 1080–22 August 1138":"umbes 1080–22. august 1138","1080–1138":"1080–1138","1093–1140":"1093–1140","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1135–1170":"1135–1170","1045–1093":"1045–1093","1047–Female":"1047–Surnud","1080":"1080","22 August 1138":"22. august 1138","1130":"1130","Abt 1125":"umbes 1125","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1093":"1093","1138":"1138","1135":"1135","1047":"1047","1079":"1079","1200":"1200","1045":"1045","13 Nov 1093":"13. november 1093","about 1130":"umbes 1130","Abt 1080":"umbes 1080","Berwick, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland","Northallerton, Yorkshire, England":"Northallerton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gordon Berwickshire, Scotland":"Gordon, Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"," Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1080–22 August 1138":"noin 1080–22. elokuuta 1138","1080–1138":"1080–1138","1093–1140":"1093–1140","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1135–1170":"1135–1170","1045–1093":"1